<LENGTH>
<P>
337 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth R. Weiss 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 HORSEFLESH: They shoot horses, don't they? Don Anderson says they do. He's the 
instructor of the soon-to-be disbanded horse-training program at Moorpark 
College. And he says he wants to prevent horseflesh dealers from buying any of 
the 40 horses that must be sold as surplus state property to the highest bidder 
(B1) . . . . "Between 75% and 80% of the horses at those sales go to the 
killers," Anderson said. "You're going to have to put me away and throw away 
the key before I let that happen." 
</P>
<P>
 TOP-RATED HAMS: As defending champs, Conejo Valley Amateur Radio Club members 
will scramble to the top of Rasnow Peak on Saturday. They'll string antennae on 
polls and mount satellite dishes on trailers. During a 24-hour marathon, the 
club's battery-powered transmitters will try to reach out and touch more ham 
radio operators than any other competitor in America. Dick Anderson expects 
half of the club's 100 members to join in the national contest: "We've won the 
last four years in a row." 
</P>
<P>
 TEEN CHALLENGE: Now that summer is here, many teen-agers face their most 
difficult decision of the year: What to do before school resumes? Some teens 
loathe the idea of breaking training as world-class couch potatoes . . . . But 
billiards are big in some cities (Ventura County Life, Page 8). There's 
skating, miniature golf, or even a summer job. It doesn't have to be drudgery. 
Magic Mountain hires 3,000 summer workers. "We're definitely in a big hiring 
mode," a spokesman says. "We've got excellent, excellent opportunities for 
teens." 
</P>
<P>
 TRADING PLACES: Sandi Webb is weary of all the attention given to sports 
heroes with feet of clay . . . . So the Simi Valley councilwoman wants the city 
to issue its own set of trading cards featuring its police officers. Their 
height, weight, arrest records and other stats could be listed on the back. 
She'd like to see police dog cards too. Said Webb: "It would boost morale and 
make officers role models more than some of these sports figures we've been 
hearing so much about." 
</P>
