<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOPICS; ENVIRONMENT; WATER AGENCIES TO FIGHT REOPENING OF LANDFILL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A coalition of local water agencies led by the Main San Gabriel Basin 
Watermaster will fight Browning Ferris Industries' decision to reopen the 
controversial Azusa Landfill to household waste. 
</P>
<P>
 The group filed a petition with the State Water Resources Control Board this 
month to stop BFI subsidiary Azusa Land Reclamation Co. from accepting 
household trash at the site, said Mark McDonald, attorney for the watermaster, 
the agency that distributes water from the San Gabriel ground water basin and 
oversees Superfund cleanup efforts of the ground water. 
</P>
<P>
 The landfill in an old rock quarry south of the Foothill Freeway began taking 
household trash again May 19. It sits atop an aquifer that supplies water to a 
million people. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's foolish to believe this landfill won't threaten the region's water 
supply," McDonald said. The San Gabriel Valley Municipal Water District, a 
coalition member, has indicated that it will sue BFI if there is any evidence 
of ground water contamination from the landfill. 
</P>
<P>
 The coalition said the state Court of Appeal and the state water board ordered 
the facility three years ago to stop taking household trash other than 
construction and demolition debris. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1991, the operator lost a lengthy battle to expand the municipal trash 
landfill by 302 acres, with the judge saying enlargement would threaten the 
aquifer. 
</P>
<P>
 But landfill operators say the court order and subsequent instructions from 
the state water board allow dumping of household waste in the existing 80-acre 
landfill and the placing of inert construction materials in the 302-acre 
expansion. At the time of the court order, they said, they thought the original 
site was full. But because of new mapping technologies and decomposition of 
waste, the company now says it has room for 160,000 truckloads of household 
waste. 
</P>
<P>
 The coalition fighting the landfill also includes the Metropolitan Water 
District of Southern California, the Three Valleys Municipal Water District and 
the Upper San Gabriel Water District. 
</P>
</TEXT>
