<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: TORRANCE; NON-RESIDENT STUDENTS WILL NEED PERMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Starting in the fall, children of Torrance workers who live outside the city 
must get a permit to attend schools in the Torrance Unified School District.  
</P>
<P>
 The school board voted unanimously Monday to revise the system that allowed 
workers' children from other districts to attend elementary and middle schools 
in Torrance. 
</P>
<P>
 District officials said enrollment has increased steadily for the past four 
years, creating the potential for overcrowding. The changes allow the district 
to give priority to Torrance residents.  
</P>
<P>
 Non-resident students who already attend school under the program will be 
allowed to continue. 
</P>
<P>
 In the fall, non-residents may enter Torrance schools only by applying for an 
inter-district permit and will be admitted only if space is available. The 
permit program requires students to maintain good records in attendance, 
academic achievement and behavior. MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
