<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; TIME TO CUT OFF 'PLAY ON' CALLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 International soccer officials said Wednesday they were unhappy with some of 
the officiating at World Cup '94, and threatened to release referees who have 
been sub-par. 
</P>
<P>
 Although he refused to identify any referees, Joseph Blatter, general 
secretary of FIFA, soccer's world governing body, said a few of the first 13 
matches were poorly officiated, among them Tuesday's Argentina-Greece game in 
Foxboro, Mass.The referee there was Arturo Angeles of Temple City in his World 
Cup debut. 
</P>
<P>
 Blatter said FIFA was disappointed by the lack of fouls for tackling from 
behind, and the roughness in guarding such stars as Diego Maradona of 
Argentina, Roberto Baggio of Italy and Romario of Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
 A review by FIFA's officiating council is expected to be completed this 
morning in Irving, Tex., but results will not be announced until Monday. Any 
referee deemed below par will be barred from calling any more games. ELLIOTT 
ALMOND 
</P>
</TEXT>
