<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; QUIET CELEBRATION, OF NECESSITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT WHITE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Carmen Martinez, a State Department official at the U.S. consulate in 
Barranquilla, Colombia, Carlos Valderrama's home town, watched and celebrated 
the U.S. team's victory with 11 other Americans. 
</P>
<P>
 "Before the game the street was full of people driving around, waving flags, 
honking horns," said Martinez. "One of the employees has a 52-inch TV, so the 
12 of us watched it at their place. After the game we drove to the office and 
it was totally quiet. No one was out. It's kind of eerie. 
</P>
<P>
 "We obviously can't go out and celebrate. But we wanted the team to know they 
made our year and we're very proud of them." MATT WHITE 
</P>
</TEXT>
