<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; NO PAY, NO PLAY, INDOMITABLE 
LIONS SAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RANDY HARVEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Major league baseball players aren't the only athletes threatening to strike. 
</P>
<P>
 Cameroon's Indomitable Lions, whose lives off the field have been dominated by 
financial problems, have threatened to be no-shows for Friday's game at Palo 
Alto against Brazil unless they are paid the money they have been promised by 
their soccer federation. 
</P>
<P>
 The bankrupt federation appealed to the government, which dispatched sports 
minister Bernard Massoua to the team's training camp at Moraga, Calif., 
Wednesday with a suitcase filled with $535,000. 
</P>
<P>
 When the players responded with a fax to the government demanding more, the 
country's president, Paul Biya, arranged for an additional $400,000 to be 
delivered today. 
</P>
<P>
 "The players are losing confidence, and they want a guarantee," said Coach 
Henri Michel, whose team tied Sweden, 2-2, in its first game Sunday at the Rose 
Bowl. "It's difficult to concentrate on games." RANDY HARVEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
