<HEADLINE>
<P>
PHILANTHROPIST CAROL CHAPMAN DIES AT 58 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Carol Chapman, a Corona del Mar art consultant, philanthropist and 
daughter-in-law of the man for whom Chapman University was named, has died 
after a long battle with cancer. She was 58. 
</P>
<P>
 Mrs. Chapman represented Oakland's Victor Fischer Gallery and sold many pieces 
of public sculpture in Orange County, including "Lightwave," a piece by 
sculptor Jerome Kirk that sits near the Chapman University auditorium. She 
later helped the university find a bust of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. 
</P>
<P>
 Mrs. Chapman and her husband, C. Stanley Chapman Jr., were on the board of the 
St. Joseph Ballet, a Santa Ana group that involves inner-city youths in dance. 
For the last two years of her life, Mrs. Chapman spent much of her time and 
energy on the troupe and last year was named volunteer of the year. 
</P>
<P>
 "Carol was one of the most positive, vivacious, can-do people I've ever 
known," said Beth Burns, artistic director of St. Joseph Ballet. "Even in the 
final days of her illness she attended rehearsals." 
</P>
<P>
 Born in Oakland, Carol Chapman met her future husband at a Stanford football 
game and married in 1958, joining one of Orange County's pioneering families. 
Her new father-in-law, C. Stanley Chapman Sr., who died in 1984, was Chapman 
University's most generous benefactor. He brought the tiny college to the city 
of Orange from Los Angeles County in 1954. 
</P>
<P>
 Mrs. Chapman is survived by her husband; two sons, Greg Chapman of Long Beach 
and Scott Chapman of Germany; a daughter, Trish Chapman of San Francisco, and a 
sister, Salle Crittendon of Alameda. 
</P>
<P>
 A viewing will be held from 4 to 7 p.m. today at Pacific View Memorial Park, 
3500 Pacific View Drive, Newport Beach. A memorial service will follow Friday 
at 11 a.m. at St. Andrew's Presbyterian Church in Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 Mrs. Chapman, who died Tuesday, will be buried in a private ceremony following 
the service. 
</P>
<P>
 The family has requested that in lieu of flowers, donations be made to her 
favorite groups: St. Joseph Ballet at 220 E. 4th St., Suite 207, Santa Ana, CA 
92701; and the Yosemite Fund, 155 Montgomery St., Suite 1104, San Francisco, CA 
94104. 
</P>
</TEXT>
