<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUNG INMATE WINS VIDEO CONTEST BUT NOT PRIZE; CYA: WENDY CREIGLOW'S 
'FLATLINES' IMPRESSED USC JUDGES. SHE COULD ATTEND THE PRESTIGIOUS FILM SCHOOL 
-- IF SHE WEREN'T LOCKED UP. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The prizewinning video's message is blunt: Drugs kill. 
</P>
<P>
 The prize is impressive: a five-week scholarship at USC's film school. 
</P>
<P>
 And the winner is miffed: A California Youth Authority inmate, she can't 
attend USC because she is serving time for grand theft auto. 
</P>
<P>
 "Flatlines," the anti-drug video written by 16-year-old Wendy Creiglow at the 
CYA's Ventura School, bested nearly 100 other student videos in May to became a 
finalist in the Teens Making a Difference contest run by KCET-TV in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Two weeks ago, it wowed the USC faculty judges, who chose it as their favorite 
for the grand prize. 
</P>
<P>
 But there is no way that Wendy Creiglow can leave, CYA officials said, because 
she must stay locked up at least until March. 
</P>
<P>
 And USC officials said they finally decided to award the scholarship to Orange 
County student Josh Goldstein, who helped produce the runner-up video, an 
AIDS-awareness clip. 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, none of the Ventura School inmates who worked on the winning video -- 
young women serving time for car theft, armed robbery and drug crimes -- will 
even be allowed to attend the awards ceremony at Dodgers Stadium on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
 And when Wendy is permitted to travel to KCET's studios Friday for a televised 
panel discussion with the hosts of "Life and Times," school officials said, she 
will be flanked by two CYA guards. 
</P>
<P>
 KCET is pleading with USC faculty to award Wendy the $4,500 scholarship after 
her release. 
</P>
<P>
 But USC officials said they do not know if they can wait that long to put the 
San Diego County teen-ager through the intensive filmmaking class at the 
university's prestigious School of Cinema-Television. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 "We haven't been able to discuss it with all the people who are involved," 
said Duke Underwood, who runs the summer production workshop for teen-age 
filmmakers. 
</P>
<P>
 Wendy said that if there is any way she can go to USC, "I'd love it." 
</P>
<P>
 "For one thing, it's something for me to do with my life," she said. "I love 
learning about new things." 
</P>
<P>
 But Wendy has not met the parole board's requirements, Ventura School Supt. 
Vivian Crawford said. Even if she had, pre-parole planning takes 60 to 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are excited about this," Crawford said. "But I have heard nothing from 
anyone who's been involved with her that says she's ready for that." 
</P>
<P>
 Wendy, who says she is a recovering alcoholic and drug abuser, took the idea 
for "Flatlines" from an anti-drug poster she drew for another class. The poster 
equated lines of cocaine with the flat readout on a machine monitoring an 
overdose victim's pulse. 
</P>
<P>
 Just 60 seconds long, the video expands on the idea and packs a graphic punch. 
</P>
<P>
 While a voice-over warns that one line leads to another, images flash in quick 
succession: a young woman snorting a line of cocaine, the red lines of a report 
card F, the hard lines of a gun barrel, the chalk outlines of a body at a 
murder scene and the flat line of a corpse's absent pulse. 
</P>
<P>
 "Drugs kill," the narrator intones, and then comes the kicker: garish yellow 
words reading, "A MESSAGE FROM WARDS OF THE CALIFORNIA YOUTH AUTHORITY." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 USC teacher Pablo Frasconi said he and the other two faculty judges believe 
that the video is extraordinary. 
</P>
<P>
 "I thought it was quite above the others in the program," said Frasconi, 
adding that the judges had no idea that "Flatlines" was made by juvenile 
inmates. 
</P>
<P>
 "The director . . . had a very strong vision of how to tie the work together, 
and also it was very strong in the area of visual language," he said. "It's too 
bad that she can't attend the workshop because it's clear that there's a lot of 
talent there that can be tapped and I guess could help them get out of the 
(crime) cycle." 
</P>
<P>
 The young Ventura School video makers -- about 15 worked on the clip -- said 
they just hope that it reaches the right people. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't like watching it 'cause it's me," said Tami Jefferson, 20, of Watts, 
who pretends to snort a line of baking soda, plays dead and provides the 
voice-over. "But I think it'll turn a lot of heads and get a lot of attention. 
</P>
<P>
 "The commercials I've seen on drugs and violence didn't get my attention, 
because if they did, I wouldn't be here," added Jefferson, who is serving time 
for armed robbery. "I just want my 5-year-old son to see it. . . . I don't want 
him to be like I am." 
</P>
<P>
 Lori Taylor, 17, serving time for a strong-arm robbery, produced the 
soundtrack, wringing electronic gunshots and queasy, threatening chords out of 
a synthesizer. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 She also was the only inmate willing to lie on the floor so that classmates 
could draw the body outlines of the staged murder scene. 
</P>
<P>
 That scene should grab young viewers "because it's scary," said Mapuana 
Pulotu, 20. While serving time for a Riverside robbery, she said, she managed 
the technical aspects of Wendy's video and three others submitted by 
inmate-students in the CYA video class. 
</P>
<P>
 "I worked hard on everything, but this was the best one," Pulotu said. 
</P>
<P>
 Brad Gardner, who runs the class, said he too hopes that teen-agers who might 
ignore conventional anti-drug messages will heed one from young women who have 
been there. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have the kids with experience in all those areas, especially drugs and 
violence, so they know it better than anyone," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 As for Wendy Creiglow's iffy prize, Gardner said he can only wait and see, and 
be glad that an entry from his class won. "It's the best thing that's happened 
to my students since I've been here," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
