<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: BUDGET SUBCOMMITTEE COULD BE DISBANDED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PHYLLIS W. JORDAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura County's once influential budget subcommittee that advises the Board 
of Supervisors on how to spend the county's money has outlived its usefulness 
and should be disbanded, board members say. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a place where you could debate and discuss before things became public 
-- and that's certainly not the case anymore," Supervisor Maggie Kildee, who 
heads the panel, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Instead, state law has opened the panel to the public and the press and, 
Kildee said, eliminated the candor and informal discussions that made the 
meetings valuable. 
</P>
<P>
 The subcommittee, which included two supervisors and 10 county department 
heads, developed such ideas as the four-day workweek and early retirement 
programs. Now agency heads often present the same information they will later 
bring to board meetings. 
</P>
<P>
 "It seems to be something of a redundant effort, doing the same thing we're 
doing at the full board," Supervisor Maria VanderKolk said. 
</P>
<P>
 Kildee called for a vote next week on whether to disband the subcommittee. 
PHYLLIS W. JORDAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
