</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles police union extended voting on the city's contract offer 
until Friday in an effort to increase officer participation. 
</P>
<P>
 Ballots will be available during the day Friday at the Police Protective 
League headquarters at 600 E. 8th Street for officers who were not able to 
attend the 11 ratification sessions scheduled for Tuesday, Wednesday and 
today.So far, roughly a third of the 7,000 LAPD officers have cast ballots, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 The results of the voting will be announced by the union Monday. The City 
Council is scheduled to consider the $50-million contract offer next Wednesday. 
The deal -- worked out behind the scenes by Mayor Richard Riordan, Councilman 
Richard Alatorre and others -- calls for a 7% pay raise over the next 18 
months, a 2% bonus for patrol officers and $1,500 in cash payments for all 
officers. 
