<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: CYPRESS; SWAP MEET CLEARS ITS LAST HURDLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has approved the redesign of an awning for a forthcoming new 
swap meet at Los Alamitos Race Course. 
</P>
<P>
 City Manager Darrell Essex said the council's approval means that the swap 
meet has now cleared all governmental hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
 "The canopy for the food concession was the only thing remaining before the 
council," Essex said. "Now everything has city approval, and the swap meet is 
scheduled to open July 9." 
</P>
<P>
 The council on June 13 approved most of the design plans for the swap meet's 
food concessions and restrooms. But the council balked at the design for an 
awning, or canopy, over the food concession. The original design was for 
something like a circus tent, with peaks and pennants. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilwoman Joyce C. Nicholson said the original design had too much of a 
"carnival atmosphere." 
</P>
<P>
 And Mayor Richard Partin jokingly had accused the canopy designer of trying to 
copy the famous twin peaks at Churchill Downs, the Kentucky Derby track in 
Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
 The new design, approved at a special meeting Monday, looks "more like a 
regular canopy," Essex said. BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</TEXT>
