<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE SEEK SHOOTING VICTIM'S EX-BOYFRIEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG HERNANDEZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Police said Wednesday that they want to question the former boyfriend of a 
23-year-old woman who was found shot to death, along with her current 
boyfriend, inside her apartment this week. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have been unsuccessful in our efforts to reach him," Lt. Robert Helton 
said of the former boyfriend, who has not been named as a suspect. 
</P>
<P>
 "If we can get to the point where we can list him as a suspect, then we will 
try and get a warrant for his arrest," Helton said. "It's going to take a 
certain level of evidence before we can get to that stage." 
</P>
<P>
 Maria Laura Suarez and 36-year-old Crisanto Flores were found dead Monday 
afternoon in her third-floor apartment in the 1100 block of West Civic Center 
Drive. 
</P>
<P>
 Neighbors say Suarez, who worked as a cocktail waitress at a Santa Ana 
nightclub, and her former boyfriend had lived together in the apartment until 
two months ago, when she forced him to leave. 
</P>
<P>
 Art Bautista, assistant manager of the apartment complex, said Suarez had not 
asked management to change her locks.  
</P>
<P>
 The victims had been dead for about 36 hours when their bodies were 
discovered. A neighbor had reported to the apartment's maintenance worker 
Sunday morning that she had heard gunshots, but the worker did not tell 
management until sometime Monday, Helton said. 
</P>
<P>
 "There was a lengthy delay as far as notifying the manager," Helton said. "We 
don't know why he didn't report it right away." 
</P>
<P>
 Bautista said the double murder has residents frightened. 
</P>
<P>
 "It doesn't matter what neighborhood you are in . . . anything can happen," 
Bautista said. "It could happen anywhere to anyone." 
</P>
<P>
 Said neighbor Max Mendez: "It happened right in front of my house. There are 
no security guards here. Anyone can get up here. I'm moving this month." 
</P>
</TEXT>
