<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: LONG BEACH; CHLORINE IN WATER PROMPTS COMPLAINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN D. WAGNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents in some sections of the city have complained that drinking water has 
turned cloudy and smells like bleach, but water officials insist that the water 
is safe to drink and should return to normal soon. 
</P>
<P>
 The Long Beach Water Department has been adding chlorine, a stronger 
disinfectant, to the water supply this month to ensure that the water remains 
safe to drink during the warm summer months when demand is higher, said 
department spokesman Robert Cole. 
</P>
<P>
 The city has been flushing water from fire hydrants to reduce the presence of 
the old disinfectants, called chloramines. The flushing has stirred up minerals 
inside older pipes in some areas of the city, giving water a cloudy appearance, 
Cole said. 
</P>
<P>
 The city had not flushed since 1987 during the annual changeovers to chlorine 
because of the drought. JOHN D. WAGNER 
</P>
</TEXT>
